# Go Project — Claude Code Instructions

_Origin: https://github.com/maxart/Go-with-AI — check upstream for newer versions of this file._

## Identity

Production Go backend service (HTTP/gRPC API or worker) on AWS (Lambda, ECS Fargate, EKS, or EC2) — or on an NVIDIA-GPU host (EC2 G/P-family, EKS with the GPU Operator, NVIDIA DGX Cloud, NVIDIA Cloud Functions). Modern best practices (2025-2026, Go 1.24+). Clean, idiomatic, type-safe, secure code that scales horizontally. Prioritize correctness, clarity, observability, operational simplicity. Don't over-engineer. Go rewards small, sharp, boring code.

---

## Output and Efficiency

- Code first; explanation only if non-obvious. No sycophantic openers, closing fluff, or restating the question. No unsolicited suggestions or boilerplate beyond scope.
- Read before writing. One focused pass — avoid write-delete-rewrite cycles. If unsure, say so. Never guess Go stdlib, AWS SDK v2 method shapes, or `go.mod` directives.
- ASCII-only output. Code review: state bug, show fix, stop. Debugging: read first, state what/where/fix. User instructions override this file.

---

## Code Quality

- Simplest code that solves the problem. **A little copying is better than a little dependency** — don't pull in a lib for one helper. No speculative abstractions.
- **Errors are values.** Return `error` from anything that can fail. Never `panic` for expected failures. `log.Fatal` only in `main`.
- **Accept interfaces, return concrete types.** Define the interface in the **consumer** package, not the producer. Tiny interfaces (1-3 methods). `io.Reader`, `io.Writer`, `error` are the model.
- One package per directory. Package name = directory name (lowercase, single word, no underscores). No circular imports.
- Don't comment what code says — only non-obvious "why". Doc-comments on every exported identifier, starting with the identifier name. Remove dead code.
- `gofmt` mandatory. `goimports` on save. CI fails on formatting drift.

### Naming

Packages: short, lowercase, no plural (`user` not `users`); no `util`/`common`/`helpers`/`models` (dumping grounds). Avoid stuttering (`http.Handler` not `http.HTTPHandler`). Exported `PascalCase`; unexported `camelCase`. Acronyms uniform case (`URL`, `HTTPClient`, `userID`). Receivers 1-2 letters, consistent across all methods on a type. Never `self`/`this`. Errors: variables `ErrNotFound`, types `NotFoundError`. Single-method interfaces end in `-er`. Test files `_test.go`; `BenchmarkXxx`, `ExampleXxx`. Constants `PascalCase`/`camelCase` — never `UPPER_SNAKE`.

---

## Go Language

### Modules, Generics, Iterators

- One `go.mod` per module at repo root; `go 1.24` (or current min) directive matches CI. `toolchain` only when reproducibility matters. `go mod tidy` before every commit; commit `go.sum`. Never edit `require` by hand — `go get pkg@version`. One major bump per PR.
- Imports grouped: stdlib / third-party / local, blank-line separated (`goimports`).
- Concrete types in signatures. Generics only when you'd otherwise duplicate code or use `any`. Never generic-ify for "future flexibility". Use `any`, not `interface{}`, in new code.
- Range-over-function iterators (1.23+) for streaming/lazy sequences only. Plain slices + `for i := range s` for collections.
- Defined types (`type UserID string`) over aliases for new domain types — real type safety; `UserID` distinct from `OrderID`.

### Errors

- Wrap with `%w`: `fmt.Errorf("get user %s: %w", id, err)`. Never `%v` for inner errors (loses chain). Sentinel errors (`var ErrNotFound = errors.New(...)`) for known failures, check with `errors.Is`. Custom error types when callers need fields, check with `errors.As`. Don't compare `err.Error()` strings.
- Don't `if err != nil { return err }` blindly — add context unless the immediate caller will. `errors.Join` (1.20+) for aggregation. Never swallow — `_ = x.Close()` is a smell.
- `panic`/`recover` only at process boundaries (HTTP middleware turning panics into 500s, `main` recovery). Never for control flow.

### Pointers, Slices, Maps, Defer

- Pointers when: value is large, you need to mutate, type has a mutex, or nil is meaningful. Otherwise pass by value — escape analysis is good, value semantics are safer.
- Slices: nil is valid for read; `make([]T, 0, cap)` when capacity known. Slicing aliases backing array — `slices.Clone` to detach.
- Maps: no concurrent writes without `sync.Mutex` (or `sync.Map` when keys stable + reads dominate). Iteration order randomized — don't depend on it.
- `defer` for cleanup at top of the function after acquiring the resource. Defers in loops accumulate — close inline or factor out.

---

## Project Structure

`cmd/<binary>/main.go` — wiring only (load config, build deps, start server, handle shutdown). No business logic. One subdir per binary.

`internal/` — private to the module (Go enforces). Default to `internal/`. `pkg/` only for code genuinely meant to be imported externally — most services have no `pkg/`.

Organize `internal/` by **domain** (`user/`, `order/`, `billing/`), not technical layer (`handlers/`, `services/`, `repos/`). A domain package owns its types, interfaces, store impl, and service. Cross-domain code goes in a coordinating package or `cmd/`.

Other dirs: `migrations/` (SQL via `golang-migrate`), `api/` (OpenAPI / `.proto`), `internal/platform/` (database init, AWS config helper, slog, OTel). Top-level `Dockerfile`, `Makefile`, `go.mod`, `go.sum`, `.golangci.yml`, `.env.example`, `.gitignore`.

Avoid `util`/`common`/`helpers`/`models` — they become dumping grounds. Name packages by what they provide.

---

## HTTP Server (net/http, Go 1.22+)

- **Default to stdlib `net/http`.** The 1.22 enhanced `ServeMux` supports method matching (`"GET /users/{id}"`), path wildcards via `r.PathValue("id")`, exact-path `{$}`. Enough for most services — no `gin`/`echo`/`chi`/`fiber`. Reach for `chi` only if you need rich middleware; `echo`/`gin` only on team familiarity. Method mismatch auto-returns 405 with `Allow`.
- Handlers are `http.HandlerFunc` or types implementing `http.Handler`. Inject deps via a struct (`type API struct { users *user.Service; logger *slog.Logger }`).
- Always set `http.Server.ReadHeaderTimeout`/`ReadTimeout`/`WriteTimeout`/`IdleTimeout` and `MaxHeaderBytes`. **Default zero values are Slowloris bait.** Graceful shutdown: catch `SIGINT`/`SIGTERM`, `server.Shutdown(ctx)` with a 30s deadline, then close DB pools and flush observability.
- Middleware = `func(http.Handler) http.Handler`. Chain via composition or a tiny helper (no framework needed for chaining). Standard order: panic recovery → request ID → logger → tracing → auth → CORS → rate-limit → handler.
- Decode bodies with `json.NewDecoder(r.Body).Decode(&v)` then `defer r.Body.Close()`. Set `dec.DisallowUnknownFields()` for strict APIs. Cap body with `http.MaxBytesReader` (~1 MiB) before decoding.
- **Never** return raw domain or DB structs as JSON — define a DTO per endpoint. Avoids leaking internal fields, accidental exposure on refactor, and coupling wire format to storage.
- Error responses: stable shape `{"error":{"code":"...","message":"..."}}`. Don't echo internal errors; map to safe public messages. Log the full error server-side with the request ID. Status codes: 200 OK, 201 Created (+ `Location`), 204, 400 client, 401, 403, 404, 409, 422 validation, 429, 5xx. Never 200 with `"success":false`.

---

## Context, Concurrency, Cancellation

- **First parameter of every blocking/I/O function is `ctx context.Context`.** Pass it through; never store in a struct field (lint: `containedctx`). In handlers use `r.Context()` — never `context.Background()`.
- `context.WithTimeout`/`WithDeadline` at the boundary where you decide the budget (handler entry, outbound call, DB query). Always `defer cancel()`. Don't add per-call timeouts inside library code — let the caller decide.
- `ctx.Done()` for cancellation; check `ctx.Err()` after `select`. `context.Cause(ctx)` (1.20+) returns the underlying reason — log this.
- `context.WithValue` only for request-scoped data crossing API boundaries (request ID, auth principal, trace span). Never for optional args. Use unexported key types (`type ctxKey int`).
- **Goroutines**: every goroutine must have an obvious termination path. Naked `go fn()` in a long-running service is a leak.
- Use `golang.org/x/sync/errgroup` for parallel work that should fail-fast: first non-nil error cancels the group context and is returned by `Wait()`. `sync.WaitGroup` only when you don't need error aggregation. Prefer channels for handoff, mutexes for state. `sync.RWMutex` only when reads vastly dominate (measure first).
- Channel rules: the **sender** closes (closing a closed channel panics). Buffered for hand-off; unbuffered for sync. Never `nil` channel in `select` unless you mean "disable this case".
- `go test -race ./...` in CI. Any `WARNING: DATA RACE` is a release blocker.

---

## Database Access (PostgreSQL with pgx + sqlc)

- **Default**: `jackc/pgx/v5` + `sqlc`. `lib/pq` is in maintenance mode — don't use for new code. `database/sql` only when driver portability matters (rare).
- One `*pgxpool.Pool` per process at startup. Tune `MaxConns` (= app concurrency cap, often 10-25/pod), `MinConns`, `MaxConnLifetime` (~30m), `MaxConnIdleTime`. Pass the pool (or generated `Querier`) into stores.
- `sqlc` generates a typed `Queries` struct from hand-written SQL in `db/queries/*.sql`. **Don't** hand-write methods that duplicate sqlc output. Always pass `ctx` — pgx honors cancellation.
- **Transactions**: `tx, err := pool.BeginTx(ctx, ...)`; `defer tx.Rollback(ctx)` (no-op if committed); `tx.Commit(ctx)` at the end. Keep them **short** — long transactions hold locks.
- **Never** build SQL with `fmt.Sprintf` from user input. Parameter placeholders only. Dynamic `IN (...)` via `pgx.NamedArgs` or `=ANY($1)` with arrays.
- Store interface lives in the **domain package**; impl `store_postgres.go` wraps sqlc `Queries`. Services depend on the interface, not the impl — enables in-memory fakes for tests.
- Migrations: `golang-migrate` (or `goose`/`atlas`). Versioned SQL in `migrations/`. **Append-only in production.** Connect with retry+backoff at startup; fail-fast on bad DSN. `pool.Ping(ctx)` in readiness probe.

---

## AWS SDK for Go v2

- **Always v2** (`github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/...`). v1 reached end-of-support **July 31, 2025** — do not start anything new on it; migrate any v1 holdouts.
- Load config once at startup: `cfg, err := config.LoadDefaultConfig(ctx, ...)`. Reuse one `aws.Config` to construct service clients. Service clients are **safe for concurrent use** — keep them as singletons.
- **Credentials**: never put access keys in env vars or files in containers. Use IAM roles — task role on ECS/Fargate, execution role on Lambda, IRSA on EKS, instance profile on EC2. Default credential chain finds them.
- **Region**: from `AWS_REGION` env (set automatically on Lambda/ECS); fail-fast if unset elsewhere. Pass `ctx` to every API call. Configure retries (`config.WithRetryMaxAttempts(5)`, adaptive mode for high-throughput).
- Use **paginators** (e.g., `s3.NewListObjectsV2Paginator(client, input)`) — never hand-roll `NextToken` loops.
- **Endpoint resolution**: don't override `BaseEndpoint` outside tests / LocalStack. For LocalStack/Minio: per-client option `o.BaseEndpoint = aws.String(endpoint)` and `o.UsePathStyle = true` for S3.
- Don't bake account-specific ARNs into code — pass via env. Don't log raw responses (PII / credentials in headers).

---

## AWS Lambda (Go)

- **Runtime**: `provided.al2023` (`go1.x` deprecated end of 2023 — builds rejected). Binary must be named `bootstrap`, zipped at root.
- **Architecture**: `arm64` (Graviton2) — **20% cheaper, ~19% faster**. Cross-compile: `GOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64 CGO_ENABLED=0 go build -tags lambda.norpc -ldflags "-s -w" -trimpath -o bootstrap .`. Fall back to `x86_64` only if a CGO dep blocks.
- Handler: `lambda.Start(handler)` from `github.com/aws/aws-lambda-go/lambda` in `main()`. Signature `func(ctx context.Context, event EventType) (ResponseType, error)`. Event types in `github.com/aws/aws-lambda-go/events`.
- **Initialize once at package level** — AWS clients, pgx pool (via RDS Proxy), config, loggers — outside `main`. Container is reused; per-invocation init burns billed time. Cold start under 60 ms is achievable on arm64 with AL2023.
- **Cold starts**: synchronous user-facing APIs use **Provisioned Concurrency** or **SnapStart** where available. Async (SQS, EventBridge) usually doesn't care.
- Don't run a long-lived HTTP server in Lambda — use API Gateway / ALB / Function URL. `aws-lambda-go-api-proxy` adapts `net/http` (acceptable for migration; native handlers are faster).
- Logs: structured JSON to stdout via `slog.JSONHandler` — CloudWatch Logs ingests; queryable via Logs Insights. Never `log.Println` plaintext. Don't `os.Exit` in a handler.

---

## AWS ECS / Fargate

- One process per container. **Multi-stage Dockerfile**: stage 1 compiles; stage 2 `FROM scratch` (or `gcr.io/distroless/static-debian12:nonroot`) with the binary + `ca-certificates`. Image < 20 MB. Build with `CGO_ENABLED=0 GOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64` and run on Graviton (`runtimePlatform: { cpuArchitecture: ARM64 }`). **Fargate has no GPUs** — for GPU workloads use ECS-on-EC2 or EKS with the GPU Operator (see GPU section).
- Listen on `PORT` env (default 8080), bind `0.0.0.0`. **Graceful shutdown**: ECS sends `SIGTERM` then waits `stopTimeout` (set 30-60s) before `SIGKILL`. Trap, stop accepting, drain in-flight, close DB pools, return.
- Health checks: `/healthz` 200 with no DB hit (liveness — only fails if hung). `/readyz` checks DB ping + critical deps (fails when overloaded). Map ALB target group to `/readyz`.
- **IAM Task Role** (app's AWS calls) vs **Execution Role** (ECS pulling image, writing logs, fetching secrets) — distinct, least privilege. Don't reuse.
- Config via env vars sourced from Secrets Manager / Parameter Store via the task definition. Don't bake secrets in the image. Don't fetch per request — read once at startup.
- Logs: JSON to stdout; `awslogs` driver ships to CloudWatch. High-volume: FireLens + Fluent Bit → S3/OpenSearch/Kinesis.
- **Fargate Spot** for interruption-tolerant workloads (batch, async workers); on-demand for user-facing. Always tolerate sudden termination. Autoscale on the right signal: CPU/mem for compute-bound; SQS depth for workers; ALB request count or target response time for HTTP. Min capacity ≥ 2 across AZs.

---

## CPU Architecture (arm64 vs amd64)

- **Default `arm64`** (Graviton2/3 on AWS) for pure-Go services — ~20% cheaper, ~19% faster. Cross-compile from any host: `GOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64 CGO_ENABLED=0`. No emulation needed.
- **Choose `amd64`** when **any** of: a CGO dep lacks arm64 wheels; the workload uses CUDA / NVIDIA GPUs (drivers + ecosystem are amd64-first); a hot path needs AVX-512 / AMX; customer / on-prem constraint is x86-only.
- **Multi-arch images** (`docker buildx --platform linux/amd64,linux/arm64`) only when consumers genuinely need both. Otherwise single-arch is simpler and faster to build. CGO multi-arch under buildx uses QEMU (slow); prefer native runners per arch in CI.
- Pin the arch in the task / Dockerfile / build script — implicit choices break when the host changes (Apple Silicon dev → x86 CI → Graviton prod is a common bug surface).

---

## GPU and NVIDIA Workloads

Go is the **service layer**, not the inference engine. Python (or C++) does the GPU math; Go handles routing, validation, auth, batching, observability, and quota in front of it. Don't call CUDA from Go.

- **Talk to inference servers over gRPC.** NVIDIA Triton, TGI, vLLM, NIM, and most serving stacks expose gRPC — generate a Go client from the `.proto` (`protoc --go_out --go-grpc_out`). For HTTP-only servers (Ollama, OpenAI-compatible), wrap `*http.Client` with `otelhttp.NewTransport`. **NIM** (NVIDIA Inference Microservices) is packaged-model containers with an OpenAI-compatible REST API — treat as any HTTP API, generous timeouts, stream where supported.
- **Hosting**: **NVCF** (NVIDIA Cloud Functions) for serverless GPU inference (pay per invocation, good for bursty); **DGX Cloud** for managed multi-tenant GPU clusters via hyperscaler partners; **EC2 G5/G6/P4/P5 + ECS-on-EC2 or EKS** for self-managed; **CoreWeave / Lambda Labs / RunPod** often cheapest raw GPU. **Fargate has no GPUs.** **EKS + NVIDIA GPU Operator** (itself in Go) is the standard Kubernetes pattern: pods request `nvidia.com/gpu: 1`, operator handles drivers / toolkit / MIG / monitoring.
- **Container images**: Go services that only **call** GPU servers stay on **distroless** — no GPU base image needed. Only the inference container needs `nvcr.io/nvidia/cuda:*-base-ubuntu*` and the `--gpus` / `nvidia.com/gpu` resource.
- **Architecture**: GPU hosts are predominantly **amd64** in AWS / Azure / GCP. CUDA-on-arm64 is mature on Jetson and Grace Hopper but lags broadly. Default `GOARCH=amd64` for binaries that run on GPU hosts or link CUDA libs.
- **CUDA via CGO is almost always wrong** — build complexity, race detector / pprof / delve degrade, Python ships CUDA features quarters faster, you lose the single static binary. Talk to a separate Python/C++ inference process over gRPC instead.
- **Observability**: scrape **DCGM** via `dcgm-exporter` (Prometheus format) — utilization, framebuffer, SM activity, power, temperature. Sidecar (ECS) or DaemonSet (EKS). Correlate with Go-side OTel traces by tagging spans with model name + version. Track cost-per-inference (request count × hourly GPU cost / GPU count).
- **Don't** auto-scale GPU instances aggressively — they cost 10-100x CPU per hour. Set min ≥ 1, max conservative, scale on queue depth or p95 latency, long cooldowns. Prefer **batching at the Go layer** (5-50 ms accumulation → single batched gRPC call) before adding GPU capacity.

---

## Configuration and Secrets

- All config from **environment variables** at startup (`os.Getenv` or a typed loader: `kelseyhightower/envconfig`, `caarlos0/env`, `sethvargo/go-envconfig`). Validate up front — fail-fast on missing/invalid.
- `Config` struct in `internal/config`. One source of truth; pass it (or relevant slices) into constructors. Never read `os.Getenv` outside `internal/config`.
- **Secrets**: AWS Secrets Manager (rotatable, versioned) or SSM Parameter Store SecureString (cheaper, no rotation). Reference from the ECS task definition / Lambda env mapping — the platform injects them as env vars. Don't fetch from Go unless rotation requires it.
- Never log config values that may contain secrets. Implement `LogValue()` / `String()` to redact. `log.Printf("config: %+v", cfg)` is a CVE waiting to happen.
- Commit `.env.example` with placeholders. Never commit `.env`. Production uses the platform's secret mechanism, not files.

---

## Logging (slog)

- Use `log/slog` (stdlib, 1.21+). **JSON handler in production** (`slog.NewJSONHandler(os.Stdout, &slog.HandlerOptions{Level: slog.LevelInfo})`); text handler locally.
- Set the package-level logger once in `main`, then pass it down (`type Service struct { logger *slog.Logger }`) — don't use the global `slog.Default()` in libraries.
- Always `*Context` variants from a handler/request: `logger.InfoContext(ctx, "user fetched", "user_id", id, "duration_ms", ms)`. Lets handlers attach trace IDs via a custom `Handler` and lets the OTel bridge correlate logs to traces.
- **Key-value attribute pairs**, not formatted strings: `slog.Info("user fetched", "user_id", id)` not `slog.Info(fmt.Sprintf(...))`. JSON handler can index attributes; formatted strings can't.
- Levels: `Debug` for dev-only detail, `Info` for normal ops, `Warn` for recoverable anomalies, `Error` for genuine failures. **Don't `Error` everything** — pages get ignored.
- **Redact secrets** via `LogValuer` interface or `ReplaceAttr` in `HandlerOptions`. Tokens, passwords, PII (email, SSN), card numbers — never raw in logs. Bridge to OpenTelemetry with `otelslog` so logs carry trace IDs and ship to your APM.

---

## Observability (OpenTelemetry, ADOT)

- Use **OpenTelemetry** for traces, metrics, and (increasingly) logs. AWS X-Ray now ingests OTLP — use **AWS Distro for OpenTelemetry (ADOT)** as the collector. Don't use the X-Ray SDK directly for new code; X-Ray is transitioning to OTel.
- Initialize a `TracerProvider` and `MeterProvider` at startup; `defer shutdown()` to flush. Set the OTLP exporter endpoint to the ADOT collector sidecar (`localhost:4317` gRPC or `:4318` HTTP).
- Auto-instrument: `otelhttp.NewHandler(mux, "api")` for the server, `otelhttp.NewTransport` for the client, `otelpgx` for pgx, `otelaws` for AWS SDK v2. These add spans, propagate trace context, and emit standard semantic-convention attributes.
- Manual spans for business operations: `ctx, span := tracer.Start(ctx, "user.create"); defer span.End()`. Attach attributes, record errors (`span.RecordError(err); span.SetStatus(codes.Error, err.Error())`).
- Metrics that pay for themselves on every service: HTTP request duration histogram (route, method, status), inflight requests gauge, DB query duration histogram, downstream RPC latency, business counters. Don't paper over missing logs with metrics or vice versa.
- **ECS deployment**: ADOT collector as a sidecar container in the same task. **Lambda**: ADOT as a Lambda layer. Both forward to X-Ray, CloudWatch Metrics, Prometheus, or OTLP-compatible backends (Datadog, Honeycomb, New Relic, Grafana).
- Tag traces and metrics with deployment metadata (service name, version, env, region, AZ) via OTel `Resource`. Sample 1-10% in prod for high-traffic; always-on for low-traffic.

---

## Validation and Input Handling

- Validate at the **edge** (HTTP / Lambda / SQS consumer). Reject early, return 400 with a clear shape — never let bad input reach the service layer.
- Request structs adjacent to the handler; validate with `go-playground/validator` (struct tags) or hand-rolled functions for one-off rules. For complex domain validation, expose a `Validate() error` method.
- Constrain sizes: max body via `http.MaxBytesReader`; max string length explicitly. Untrusted strings into URLs / SQL / shell / templates always escaped (`html/template`, `net/url.QueryEscape`, parameterized SQL, never `os/exec` with shell strings).
- Treat **all** external input as untrusted: HTTP bodies, query/path params, headers, cookies, env vars in pipelines, S3 object contents, SQS message bodies. Trust nothing, validate everything.

---

## Error Handling Patterns

- Wrap with **context** at each layer: `fmt.Errorf("user.GetByID id=%s: %w", id, err)`. Top of the call stack should produce a debuggable chain.
- Map errors to status / response in the **handler** layer via `errors.Is`/`errors.As`. Service and repository layers don't know about HTTP — they return domain or wrapped errors.
- Sentinel errors at package boundaries (`var ErrNotFound = errors.New(...)`) — callers test with `errors.Is`. Custom error types when callers need fields (`var verr *ValidationError; if errors.As(err, &verr) { ... }`).
- Don't expose raw errors to clients. Handler logs the full chain; returns a sanitized message keyed by an error code. Public errors must not leak DB internals, paths, or stack traces.
- `panic` only for truly unrecoverable conditions at startup or programmer bugs. Production HTTP middleware **must** recover panics and turn them into 500s (logged with stack via `runtime/debug.Stack()`); without this, one bad goroutine kills the process.

---

## Security (Non-Negotiable)

- **SQL injection**: parameter placeholders only — never `fmt.Sprintf` user input into SQL. `sqlc` makes this nearly impossible. `gosec` rules `G201`/`G202`.
- **Command injection**: never `exec.Command("sh", "-c", userInput)`. Separate args; validate `cmd` against an allow-list. `gosec G204`.
- **Path traversal**: `filepath.Clean` then check `strings.HasPrefix(cleaned, allowed)`. Never `os.Open(userInput)`.
- **SSRF**: validate user-supplied URLs — host in allow-list, scheme `https`. Custom `http.Client` with a `DialContext` blocking RFC 1918 / link-local for outbound calls accepting user URLs.
- **TLS**: `crypto/tls` with `MinVersion: tls.VersionTLS12` (TLS 1.3 where you control both ends). Never `InsecureSkipVerify: true` outside tests.
- **Crypto**: `crypto/rand` for tokens / IDs / nonces — **never** `math/rand`. Passwords: `argon2id` (preferred), `bcrypt` (cost ≥ 12), or `scrypt`. Never SHA/MD5 for passwords.
- **Sessions**: opaque session IDs in **httpOnly Secure SameSite=Strict cookies** backed by Redis/DDB. If JWT: asymmetric (RS256/Ed25519) with rotation; verify `aud`/`iss`/`exp`/`nbf`; force expected `alg` (never trust header `alg`).
- **Secrets in source/logs**: `gitleaks` or `trufflehog` pre-commit; `gosec G101` flags hard-coded credentials. Never log `Authorization` headers or auth-endpoint bodies.
- **Dependencies**: `govulncheck ./...` in CI (analyzes call graph — only flags vulns you actually call). `gosec ./...` for SAST. Critical/high are release blockers. Dependabot / Renovate; one major bump per PR.
- **Races**: `go test -race ./...` in CI. Any data race is a security concern (TOCTOU, partially-constructed objects, panics).

---

## Testing

- **Stdlib `testing` is enough.** `stretchr/testify` (`require`, `assert`) is fine but optional. Avoid BDD frameworks (`ginkgo`).
- **Table-driven tests** are the idiomatic pattern: slice of `{name, in, want, wantErr}` structs; `for _, tc := range cases { t.Run(tc.name, ...) }`. Use `t.Run` always (selective filtering, parallel control, clearer output). `t.Parallel()` everywhere safe.
- Test **behavior**, not implementation. Test exported functions through their public surface. `pkg_test` package (black-box) for true public-API tests; same `pkg` package for internal-detail tests.
- **Mocks**: prefer hand-written fakes (in-memory map implementing the store interface). Generated mocks (`mockery`, `gomock`) only for large stable interfaces. Never mock what you don't own — wrap the third-party type in your own interface, mock that.
- **Integration tests with `testcontainers-go`** for real Postgres / Redis / LocalStack — spins a Docker container per test (or per package via `TestMain`), tears it down. Gate with `//go:build integration` so unit tests stay fast.
- HTTP handlers: `httptest.NewRecorder()` + `handler.ServeHTTP(rr, req)`; assert on `rr.Code` / `rr.Body`. Full server: `httptest.NewServer(mux)`.
- Coverage: `go test -coverprofile=cov.out -covermode=atomic ./...`. Don't chase 100% — chase critical paths and edge cases. **`go test -race`** non-negotiable in CI. Fuzz (`func FuzzXxx(f *testing.F)`) for parsers, validators, anything taking untrusted bytes.

---

## Build, Cross-Compile, Deploy

- `go build` is enough — no Make required for build, but a `Makefile` is a fine entry point for `lint`/`test`/`tidy`/`build`/`docker`/`deploy`. CI replays Makefile targets.
- **Reproducible builds**: `-trimpath -ldflags "-s -w -X main.version=${VERSION} -X main.commit=${COMMIT}"`. Inject version/commit via `-X`, not runtime magic.
- **CGO_ENABLED=0** for portable static binaries — required for `FROM scratch` images and AL2023 Lambda. CGO only when truly necessary (e.g., native SQLite); accept the runtime dep tradeoff.
- Cross-compile: `GOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64 go build` from any host. No emulation; faster than building inside Docker on the target arch.
- **Docker**: multi-stage. Stage 1 `golang:1.24-alpine` builds. Stage 2 `gcr.io/distroless/static-debian12:nonroot` (or `scratch`) copies binary + `ca-certificates` (+ `tzdata` if needed). `USER nonroot:nonroot`. Final image < 20 MB.
- Image scanning: Trivy / Grype in CI. Critical CVEs in the final image (not the build stage) are blockers. Re-scan deployed images on a schedule.
- Deploy artifacts: container images for ECS/EKS/EC2; zip for Lambda. Always tag with the Git SHA, never `latest` in production.

---

## Tooling

- **Required**: `gofmt` (or `goimports`), `go vet`, `golangci-lint` (curated set: `errcheck`, `govet`, `staticcheck`, `unused`, `ineffassign`, `gosec`, `gocyclo`, `gosimple`, `revive`, `misspell`, `gocritic`, `errorlint`, `nilerr`, `bodyclose`, `containedctx`, `contextcheck`, `noctx`, `sqlclosecheck`, `tparallel`, `paralleltest`). Pin the linter version in CI; `.golangci.yml` in repo root.
- `govulncheck ./...` in CI on every PR. `gosec ./...` for SAST. `go test -race ./...` always. `go mod tidy` and `go mod verify` on every CI run — fail if `go.mod`/`go.sum` would change.
- **`pprof`**: expose `net/http/pprof` on a separate admin listener (never the public port). Profile in production, not on a laptop. **`benchstat`** for benchmark comparison: `go test -bench=. -benchmem -count=10` then diff. Don't trust single-run benchmarks.
- IDE: `gopls` (official LSP). `gopls.staticcheck: true`. `delve` debugger.
- Optional: `air` / `wgo` / `reflex` for hot-reload in dev; `task` (Taskfile) as Make alternative; `goreleaser` for multi-arch release artifacts.

---

## Performance and Resource Tuning

- Profile before optimizing. **`go test -bench=. -benchmem -cpuprofile=cpu.out -memprofile=mem.out`** at the package level; `pprof` for live processes. Don't optimize from intuition.
- **`GOMAXPROCS`**: defaults to host CPU count, which is wrong on Kubernetes / ECS where the container has a CPU limit but the host has many cores — leads to GC contention and runaway scheduler. Use `automaxprocs` (`go.uber.org/automaxprocs`) — reads cgroup limits and sets `GOMAXPROCS` correctly.
- **`GOMEMLIMIT`** (1.19+): set to ~80% of the container memory limit. Runtime GCs harder near the limit, dramatically reducing OOMKills under spikes. Set via env in the task definition.
- **`GOGC`**: default 100 is fine for most. Tune to 50 (more frequent GC, lower memory) or 200 (less GC, higher memory) based on profiling. `GOMEMLIMIT` makes manual `GOGC` tuning rarely necessary.
- **Allocations dominate latency** more than CPU in most Go services. `pprof -alloc_objects` to find hotspots. Pre-size slices/maps when capacity known. `sync.Pool` for short-lived objects in hot paths. `strings.Builder` over `+=`. Avoid `[]byte`↔`string` conversions in tight loops.
- HTTP: reuse `http.Client` and its `Transport`. Tune `Transport.MaxIdleConnsPerHost` upward (default 2 is too low for backend-to-backend traffic). Set `Timeout` on the client.

---

## Large Project Maintenance

- **Dependencies**: `go list -m -u all` monthly. `govulncheck` per PR. One major bump per PR. Pin versions in `go.mod`; commit `go.sum`. `go mod why -m <module>` to find what pulls a transitive dep.
- **Dead code**: `staticcheck` `U1000` flags unused; remove ruthlessly. `deadcode` for cross-package. Don't keep "in case we need it later" — Git remembers.
- **Refactoring**: only when the task requires or you've been asked. One thing per PR. Tests first, then change. Flag tech debt; don't silently fix.
- **Migration / large changes**: incremental. New behavior behind a flag (env var, feature flag service); old and new coexist; flip the flag; remove old code in a follow-up PR. Document the canonical pattern in this file.
- **Performance budgets**: SLO per endpoint (p50, p95, p99); CI benchmark check on hot paths; alert on regression. Track service-level metrics in production (RED: rate, errors, duration; USE: utilization, saturation, errors).
- **Module boundaries**: when `internal/` grows beyond ~10 domain packages, consider splitting into multiple modules (monorepo with `go.work`). Don't split prematurely.

---

## When Creating a New Go Service

1. `go mod init github.com/<org>/<service>`. `go 1.24` (or current). Create `cmd/api/main.go`, `internal/`, `Makefile`, `Dockerfile`, `.golangci.yml`, `.env.example`, `.gitignore`.
2. Wire basics: `slog` JSON logger, `automaxprocs`, `GOMEMLIMIT`, env loading, graceful shutdown, `/healthz` + `/readyz`. Stdlib `net/http` with `ServeMux`.
3. Pick infra: Postgres (`pgx` + `sqlc`) or DynamoDB (`aws-sdk-go-v2/service/dynamodb`). Migrations (`golang-migrate`). Pool ping in `/readyz`.
4. OpenTelemetry init (`otelhttp`, `otelpgx`/`otelaws`). OTLP exporter → ADOT collector sidecar.
5. CI: `go vet`, `go test -race -coverprofile=cov.out ./...`, `golangci-lint run`, `govulncheck ./...`, `go build`, container build + push, integration tests with `testcontainers-go` (gated `//go:build integration`).
6. Deploy: multi-stage Dockerfile → distroless/scratch; ECS Fargate with task + execution roles (least privilege); CloudWatch logs; ALB or API Gateway; auto-scale on CPU + ALB request count.
7. Commit `.env.example`. Never commit `.env` or AWS credentials. Lambda variant: `bootstrap`, AL2023 runtime, arm64.

---

## When Working on an Existing Project

1. Read relevant files first — `cmd/` entry, `internal/<domain>/`, store impl, related handler, `Makefile`, `Dockerfile`, `.golangci.yml`.
2. Match existing conventions even if they differ from these rules — consistency beats theoretical best practices. If they use `gin` or `chi`, use it; don't migrate without approval.
3. Don't refactor unrelated code; don't add types/comments to code you didn't change; don't introduce new libs without explicit approval. Match existing naming, file organization, error wrapping style.
4. Trace data flow: handler → service → store. Don't skip layers (handler reaching into store) unless that's the existing pattern.
5. Audit context: every function on the path takes `ctx` and passes it down. Long-running goroutines listen on `ctx.Done()`.
6. Audit observability: new endpoint → spans + metrics + structured logs with the request ID. New downstream call → traced via `otelhttp` / `otelaws` / `otelpgx`.
7. Run `go vet`, `golangci-lint run`, `go test -race ./...`, `go mod tidy` before committing.

---

## Pre-Completion Checklist

- [ ] `gofmt`, `go vet`, `golangci-lint`, `go test -race`, `go mod tidy`, `govulncheck` all pass (or document why a step wasn't run)
- [ ] Every exported identifier has a doc comment starting with the identifier name
- [ ] Every blocking/I/O function takes `ctx context.Context` as first parameter; no `context.Background()` in handlers/library code
- [ ] All errors wrapped with `%w` and context; `errors.Is`/`errors.As` used (not string compare); no swallowed errors
- [ ] No `panic` outside `main` startup or recovery middleware; `log.Fatal` only in `main`
- [ ] No SQL built with `fmt.Sprintf` from user input; all queries parameterized; bodies size-capped via `MaxBytesReader`; all input validated
- [ ] No secrets in code, env defaults, logs, or commits; `crypto/rand` (not `math/rand`) for tokens; httpOnly Secure cookies for sessions
- [ ] HTTP server has `ReadHeaderTimeout`/`ReadTimeout`/`WriteTimeout`/`IdleTimeout`; graceful shutdown on SIGTERM
- [ ] Goroutines have an obvious termination path; concurrent map writes guarded; `errgroup` used for parallel fail-fast
- [ ] Logs are structured JSON (`slog`); request ID + trace ID propagated; no PII / tokens / Authorization headers logged
- [ ] OTel spans cover new business operations and downstream calls; HTTP / DB / AWS clients auto-instrumented
- [ ] DTOs returned to clients (no raw domain or DB types); error responses have stable shape; no internal errors leaked
- [ ] AWS SDK v2 clients are singletons; `ctx` passed; paginators used; no v1 code introduced
- [ ] Dockerfile multi-stage with distroless/scratch; `CGO_ENABLED=0`; arch chosen explicitly (arm64 default; amd64 if CGO / GPU / AVX-512 / customer); image scanned
- [ ] GPU work goes through gRPC to Triton/NIM; CUDA not called from Go via CGO; DCGM metrics scraped
- [ ] Tests added: table-driven with `t.Parallel()`; integration tests gated by tag; `t.Run` for subtests; race detector clean
- [ ] No CI/CD files modified without approval; no `go get -u ./...` of unrelated deps; new deps justified

---

